<H3> <TI>   Government Minister Sees `No Reason' To Decree Mobilization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302175994 Quito Cadena Ecuador Radio in Spanish 1707 GMT 
3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0302175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Cadena Ecuador Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Patricio Gonzalez from the "Informative Antenna" </F>
newscast] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The government is making its 
first assessments of the situation of the nationwide strike. 
Government Minister Marcelo Santos Vera expressed a few minutes 
ago that it is not necessary to declare a state of mobilization 
[estado de mobilizacion] in the country, because protests have 
not been violent. He said the situation is calm -- a view we do 
not share. Let us listen: 
  [Begin recording] [Santos] We are receiving constant reports 
on the strike. Obviously, the situation is not normal. Urban 
transportation has been largely reduced in some of the most 
important cities of the country. There are demonstrations. 
There is uncertainty. Nevertheless, I do not think this should 
take us to the extreme point of thinking about more drastic 
measures. 
  [Unidentified reporter] [question indistinct] 
  [Santos] Not so far. As the situation now stands, there is 
no reason to decree a mobilization. We do not know the plans of 
the FUT [United Workers Front] leaders. I hope that in response 
to appeals from government officials and media representatives, 
they conduct their protests peacefully. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

