<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Bulletin Says 130 Arrested in Disturbances </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302204394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1823 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Quito, 3 Feb (EFE) -- According to an official 
government bulletin, 10 policemen have been seriously injured 
and 130 demonstrators have been arrested in Ecuador within the 
past seven days as the result of disturbances in several cities 
prompted by an increase in gasoline prices. The bulletin was 
released today, with the country partially paralyzed by a 
general 24-hour strike called by labor unions and other sectors 
demanding that the government repeal the higher gasoline prices. 
  Several Quito radio stations have reported numerous clashes 
betweeen demonstrators and police in Quito, Cuenca, Guayaquil, 
and other cities during the morning. The police bulletin gave 
no figures for injured or arrested demonstrators [as received], 
but witnesses and the media are reporting that they run into the 
hundreds. 
  Leaders of the United Workers Front [FUT], the country's 
largest labor federation, said at noon that the strike is 
"widespread." FUT President Edgar Ponce said in a news 
conference that "the response has been very positive." He 
declared that, if the government fails to repeal the gasoline 
price hike, another strike, this time for an "indefinite time," 
will be called. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

