<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Rejects U.S. Human Rights Hearings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302152194 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0435 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0302152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Mexican deputies and senators have condemned foreign 
intervention in Mexican affairs. The congressional Permanent 
Commission has referred to the fact that the U.S. House of 
Representatives has instituted a series of hearings to evaluate 
the status of human rights in various places in the world, 
including the events in Chiapas. 
  Despite certain coincidences, the six Mexican political 
parties have failed to reach a consensus, however; consequently, 
two different points of agreement were produced to establish the 
position of the Mexican Congress. Senator Gustavo Salinas has 
read a statement in the name of the PRI [Revolutionary 
Institutional Party], the PPS [Popular Socialist Party], the 
Cardenist Front for the National Reconstruction Party, and PARM 
[Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution]. 
  [Begin Senator Salinas recording] The congressional 
Permanent 
Commission hereby rejects absolutely the idea of hearings being 
held in the U.S. House of Representatives to debate matters that 
are exclusively Mexican. Such activities cannot be permitted to 
lead to intervention in our country. [end recording] 
  PRD [Party for the Democratic Revolution] Deputy Alejandro 
Encinas spoke in the name of his party and PAN [National Action 
Party]. 
  [Begin Encinas recording] We think it is desirable for the 
Mexican Congress to call for public hearings on violations of 
human rights, particularly against Mexicans living in the United 
States. This is a duty we should do as responsible citizens. 
[end recording] 
  During the Permanent Commission session, it was agreed that 
no special sessions will be held in February and that a 
consensus should be sought among all parties. 

</TEXT>

