<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denounces Hearings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302144394 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0302144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Good Morning From Mexico" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Foreign Secretariat has denounced hearings at 
the U.S. Congress requested by Congressman Robert Torricelli, 
and it has described the move as open intervention and 
anti-Mexican. 
  Deputy Foreign Secretary Andres Rozental said Mexicans find 
this attempt to cast judgment and besmirch our country's 
reputation to be unacceptable. He added that the move is 
apparently stems from the resentment of some people who do not 
like the fact that Mexico maintains normal relations with Cuba 
or who may be upset by the approval of NAFTA. 
  It must be made very clear, according to the official, that 
the implementation of NAFTA grants no one outside of Mexico the 
right to judge matters that are solely up to the Mexicans to 
resolve. We have never accepted, nor will we accept, the 
exercise of trusteeships over our sovereignty, Rozental stated. 

</TEXT>

