<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Replies to Peace Commissioner's Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402035594 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0153 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402035594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Indian Revolutionary Clandestine 
Committee-General Command [CCRI-CG] of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN] has issued a new communique addressed to 
Samuel Ruiz Garcia, bishop of San Cristobal de las Casas and 
national mediation commissioner, and to Manuel Camacho Solis, 
commissioner for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas. The 
communique, dated 31 January 1994, has three points. 
  The first point reads: We received the letter from Peace 
Commissioner Camacho Solis dated 29 January 1994 regarding the 
release of Division General Absalon Castellanos Dominguez. We 
have confirmed that the 38 prisoners mentioned were indeed 
released. Division General Castellanos Dominguez is in perfect 
health and knows he will be released soon. Division General 
Absalon Castellano will definitely be released. 
  The second point of the communique reads: We received the 
letter from Peace Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis dated 29 
January 1994 regarding the establishment of buffer or gray 
zones. We inform you that we fully agree with the entire 
proposal from the peace commissioner for peace and 
reconciliation in Chiapas in this respect. 
  The third point of the EZLN communique reads: In saluting 
the clear intentions of the commissioner for peace and 
reconciliation in Chiapas to make advancements to alleviate the 
grave situation affecting the civilian population in the 
conflict areas, the CCRI-CG will order the immediate withdrawal 
of EZLN troops from Los Ejidos, San Miguel, Ococingo 
Municipality, and Guadalupe Tepeyac, Las Margaritas 
Municipality. The EZLN troops will withdraw once the 
International Red Cross occupies these two buffer or gray zones 
and installs its camps for humanitarian aid. 
  The communique is signed by Subcommander Marcos and issued 
in 
the mountains of southeastern Mexico. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

