<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 2 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302195594 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302195594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Peruvian economic developments monitored through 2 
February; source is in parentheses following each item. 
  The National Bank will finance $40 million, which the 
Transportation, Communication, Housing, and Construction 
Ministry will use for infrastructure works. According to an 
executive decree published in the newspaper EL PERUANO, a joint 
operation between the two institutions to use funds from a loan 
granted by the Export and Import Bank of Japan was authorized. 
(Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network in Spanish 1800 GMT 26 
Jan 94) 
  Economy and Finance Minister Jorge Camet has said the U.S. 
Government will reportedly pay in two weeks the first 
$30-million installment, which was promised in an agreement 
signed with the Support Group. He has added this was made 
possible thanks to the recent visit by Alexander Watson, 
assistant secretary of state for Inter-American Affairs. Camet 
has also said the January inflation rate reached 1.8 percent and 
that there will be salary raises in 1994. (Lima Global de 
Television Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 1 Feb 94) 
  Felix Murillo, National Statistics and Information 
Technology 
Institute chief, has said power, water, housing, and fuel 
services, which grew by an average of 4.1 percent, are the 
sectors that increased the most. The food sector grew by only 
1.1 percent. Murillo said this prompted a compensatory effect in 
the January inflation rate, which reached 1.84 percent. (Lima 
Radio Programas del Peru Network in Spanish 1800 GMT 1 Feb 94) 
  Raul Otero, Special Privatization Committee member, has said 
the international bidding for the sale of the Hilo Copper 
Refinery was declared vacant, because there were no bids. The 
representatives of such international corporations as Maruven 
Inc., Mitsui, and Sauder Peru Copper Corporation have declined 
to submit bids, because they have claimed the $75-million base 
price was too high. (Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network in 
Spanish 1800 GMT 2 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32251 </DOCNO>
