<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transportation Board Ends Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302202194 Paris AFP in Spanish 1924 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 3 Feb (AFP) -- The four-day-old 
strike of cargo transportation vehicles in Guatemala ended today 
after the government accepted all of the demands of businessmen 
and pledged in writing to respect them, a transportation 
association official has reported. 
  The National Transportation Coordinating Board (CNT) 
announced it ordered all of its members to suspend the strike 
"immediately" because President Ramiro de Leon Carpio gave a 
"favorable" response to all of their demands. The resolution to 
the conflict came at a time when the supply of fuel at gas 
stations was beginning to run out and officials feared the 
nation would become paralyzed within the next 48 hours. 
  According to a CNT communique, telephone conversations were 
maintained "until the predawn hours" with President de Leon, who 
finally accepted the increase in rates and other demands made by 
transportation workers. The president had threatened to 
intervene and cancel current concessions with the striking 
businesses, transferring them to other enterprises. 
Nevertheless, De Leon ultimately yielded to the pressure of 
transportation businessmen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

