<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 2 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302173694 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302173694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Nicaraguan economic developments monitored through 2 
February; source follows in parentheses after each item. 
  President Violeta Chamorro inaugurated a stock exchange on 1 
February for the first time in Nicaraguan history. This stock 
exchange will strengthen the national financial system, and, 
according to President Chamorro, its creation places Nicaragua 
on par with other Central American nations. (Managua Sistema 
Nacional de Television Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 1 Feb 94) 
  The government estimated today the five-day-old 
transportation strike caused losses of approximately 60 million 
cordobas, or, more than $9 million. An economist has said from 
that amount, which represents for Nicaragua the revenues earned 
from the total production of coffee, the government has lost 
over 3 million cordobas, the equivalent of $500,000, in taxes. 
(Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish 29 Jan 94 p 12) 

</TEXT>

