<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Development Bank Reports 1994 Credit Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20320D </F>
<F P=103> 94P20320D </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish of 9 
January 1994 on page 12 reports that the National Development 
Bank (Banades) will make available 1.296 billion cordobas in 
loans to small and medium producers for the 1994-95 crop year. 
According to the article, the bank will attempt to eliminate the 
credit policy which concentrates the bulk of the available 
resources in the hands of just a few growers. The bank estimates 
that the new policy will reach an additional 9,700 customers for 
a total of 42,700; interest rates will range between 16 and 18 
percent. Silvio Baltodano, assistant credit manager at Banades, 
says that the bank will target nontraditional products, and that 
loans will be made to those in a position to pay off their 
loans. According to the article, for short-term financing 
Banades will devote 454.3 million cordobas for agriculture, 
248.5 million for cattle, and 189 million for trade and 
industry. Long-term financing will total 403.9 million cordobas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

