<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Confiscation Bonds To Be Revalued </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20320C </F>
<F P=103> 94P20320C </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish of 13 
January 1994 on page 12 reports that, according to Finance 
Minister Emilio Pereira, in 1994 the government will back 
compensation bonds issued to owners of confiscated property for 
up to 954 million cordobas. Bonds were issued last year for 720 
million cordobas. Pereira urged bondholders not to sell their 
bonds at low prices. He explained that bonds can be used to pay 
taxes on capital goods and to pay utilities. Government assets 
to be sold to back the bonds include farm equipment, land, and 
businesses. Pereira said that thus far 328 people have received 
compensation bonds for confiscated property. The article reports 
that bonds awarded last year were used to purchase tractors, 
land, and construction equipment for a total of 143,605,000 
cordobas. As soon as the bonds were first issued, owners began 
to sell them through newspaper advertisements, according to the 
article. 

</TEXT>

