<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Creation of Deputy Minister Posts Explained </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20320A </F>
<F P=103> 94P20320A </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish of 11 
January 1994 on page 12 reports that the new deputy minister 
posts in the Presidency Ministry were created in order to 
"delegate responsibilities and lighten the workload," according 
to Tomas Delaney, deputy minister for State Affairs. Delaney 
explains that his position was designed to coordinate the 
activities of the Executive branch with the Legislative, 
Judicial, and Electoral branches. Dayton Caldera, deputy 
minister for Government Affairs and director of the National 
Corporation of the Public Sector, denies that the new portfolios 
will add to the bureaucracy. Rather, according to the article, 
his duties include "coordinating the work of the Presidency and 
the Cabinet." The new deputy minister for Civilian Affairs, 
Boanerges "Pepe" Matus, is responsible for "civilian and private 
organizations, trade unions, and agencies in the country's 
interior." 

</TEXT>

