<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 2 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302172394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302172394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 2 
February. 
  The Colombian Government has decided to cut its 1994 budget 
by 369.8 billion pesos in order to stop the revaluation of the 
peso and to ease the achievement of keeping the inflation under 
the 19-percent mark. Finance Minister Rudolf Hommes has said 
this will cause the budget deficit to drop to only .16 percent 
of the gross domestic product. The government will subtract 
171.8 billion pesos from operation costs; 50 billion pesos will 
be saved in foreign debt payments and 98 billion pesos in 
investment. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 22 Jan 94, 
p 1B) 
  The National Administrative Department of Statistics (Dane) 
and the National Customs and Tax Directorate have reported that 
while imports grew by 49.7 percent in the first 10 months of 
1993, exports grew by only 2 percent. Imports amounted to $8.08 
billion, compared to $5.403 billion over the same period in 
1992. The increase in imports was due mainly to the boom in the 
construction sector; coal was the only traditional export 
product that achieved a growth. Coal exports grew from $429 
million over the first 10 months of 1992 to $463 million in 
1993. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 27 Jan 94, p 1B) 
  Antonio Pretelt Emiliani, president of the Colombian Coal 
Enterprise (Carbocol), announced on 27 January that Carbocol 
will be put on sale this year and that, although the evaluation 
that will allow the authorities to set its minimum price is yet 
to be carried out, its approximate value is $1 billion. Pretelt 
confirmed the government is willing to privatize the state-owned 
portion of the Cerrejon coal mining complex, which includes part 
of the railroad and the port. He also said the enterprise has 
reduced its liabilities by $900 million and now has only $800 
million in debts. The Cerrejon Mine exported 13.8 million tons 
of coal during 1993 for an amount of 371.570 billion pesos ($464 
million). (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 28 Jan 94, p 
2B) 
  On 1 February Dane announced the inflation rate for January. 
It was 3.15 percent, which is less than the rate for January 
1993, when inflation grew by 3.24 percent. The cost of 
transportation increased by 9.23 percent, and the cost of food 
increased by 3.94 percent. (Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision 
Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 2 Feb 94) 
  An economic report released by the Invest in Colombia 
Corporation states that foreign investment in Colombia increased 
by 24.6 percent in 1993 as compared to 1992. The majority of 
foreign investment went into the manufacturing sector, which 
received $198 million. The report states that some of the 
countries that invested the most in Colombia in 1993 were the 
United States, with 57.7 percent; Venezuela, with 15.1 percent; 
and Panama, which invested $49 million. The European country 
that invested the most was Sweden, with $27.7 million. (Mexico 
City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1753 GMT 2 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

