<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402152794 </F>
<F P=103> PA0402152794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Panamanian economic developments monitored through 2 
February. 
  Planning Minister Delia de Cardenas reported today the 
Panamanian Government had taken the first step to restructure 
its foreign debt with private banks by issuing bonds for more 
than $450 million in European Currency Units, Yens, and 
Eurobonds. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0202 GMT 1 Feb 94) 
  An Economic Commission for Latin America (ECLA) report has 
stated that Panama attained its economic recovery goal for 1992 
after the crisis of 1988 to 1989 by registering an 8-percent 
growth. According to the latest statistics available at the 
Comptroller General's Office, the Panamanian economy registered 
a 5.9-percent growth in its gross domestic product, and 
unemployment decreased from 14.2 percent to 12.5 percent in 
1992. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 31 Jan 94 p 17a) 
  According to a document issued by the National Baking 
Commission, the international banking center that operates in 
Panama increased its assets by 11 percent in the last quarter of 
1993 as compared to the same period in 1992. (Panama City LA 
PRENSA in Spanish 26 Jan 94 p 11a) 
  Panama's fuel debt with Mexico and Venezuela is more than 
$250 million, while interests accumulate at a rate of $800,000 
per month, Roberto Alfaro, commerce and trade minister, reported 
yesterday. Panama has presented two proposals to negotiate the 
fuel debt and is waiting for the response from both governments. 
(Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0001 GMT 26 Jan 94) 
  Eduardo Stein, president of the Foundation for the Economic 
and Social Development of Central America, has told members of 
the Panamanian Association of Business Executives regarding 
NAFTA that because 70 percent of Panama's gross domestic product 
is represented by the service sector, it, therefore, has a 
significant negotiating advantage over the rest of the Central 
American nations. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 29 
Jan 94 p 11a) 

</TEXT>

