<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302183394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302183394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Panamanian elections, 
which are scheduled for 8 May 1994, monitored through 3 February. 
  Pedro Vallarino Cox, president of the National Renewal 
Movement (Morena), has invited Ruben Blades, presidential 
candidate for the Papa Egoro Movement, to support the 
presidential candidacy of Ruben Dario Carles. When asked if 
Morena has been set aside now that the Nationalist Liberal 
Republican Movement (Molirena) has decided to name Carles as its 
presidential candidate, Vallarino Cox replied: "Carles is the 
Morena candidate, and I welcome the decision by other parties to 
support Carles." Presidential candidate Carles has visited 
David, Chiriqui Province, in the company of Molirena and Morena 
sympathizers. Carles told his supporters: "I am offering a 
government that will resolve problems with actions." (Panama 
City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 24 Jan 94) 
  Tomas Cabal writes in his "Hidden Truths" column that the 
candidacy of Ruben Dario Carles has gained strength now that 
Molirena has decided to support him. He adds: "Many in the 
Arnulfist Party and Authentic Liberal Party are also endorsing 
Carles, even though those two parties are supporting Mireya de 
Gruber's presidential candidacy." (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA 
in Spanish 30 Jan 94 p6a) 
  Cesar Aparicio, secretary general of the National 
Integration 
Movement (Mina), announced during a news conference on 28 
January that the party's rank and file members are "going to 
support the presidential bid of Jose Salvador Munoz of the 
Doctrinaire Panamenist Party (PPD)." Earlier, Mina President 
Arrigo Guardia had thrown his support behind Molirena candidate 
Carles. Aparicio added the PPD will allow certain prominent 
Mina figures to run for office under the PPD banner. (Panama 
City LA PRENSA in Spanish 29 Jan 94 p4) 
  Talking to San Miguelito residents, presidential candidate 
Ruben Dario Carles has promised to upgrade social services, such 
as education, health, transportation, and security. He has 
said: "The Metropolitan Sanitation Directorate has sufficient 
workers and equipment to collect garbage, but it is not doing 
its job." (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 
GMT 31 Jan 94) 
  During a news conference, Carles has vowed he will strive 
"to 
stamp out corruption, influence peddling, nepotism, and 
cronyism." He has said the democratic regime that began on 20 
December 1989 "has been timid about ending corruption," adding 
he will take a hardline position against it with popular 
support. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 2 Feb 94 p2) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

