<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Niehaus Confident of Winning OAS Secretary General Post </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201043194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2201043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by special envoy Jorge Koura in Costa Rica for the </F>
"24 Hours" newscast] 
  [Text] Costa Rican Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus told the 
"24 Hours" newscast that his election as OAS secretary general 
is guaranteed. He added that he is confident that Colombian 
President Cesar Gaviria will not run for the post. 
  The Costa Rican foreign minister said he has been virtually 
elected OAS secretary general because he has the confirmed 
support of 23 countries: He needs 18 votes to be elected. 
  [Begin Niehaus recording] If elections are held without 
pressure -- in Costa Rica we call it arm twisting -- we will 
obviously win. [end recording] 
  Referring to the possible confirmation of Colombian 
President 
Cesar Gaviria's candidacy to the post, he clearly suggested that 
Gaviria give up the possibility of officially announcing his 
candidacy. 
  [Begin Niehaus recording] Twenty-two or 23 countries are 
convinced this is fair. I am sure other countries will join 
them. Above all, I am sure -- and I say it with great respect -- 
that President Gaviria will take these aspects into 
consideration and abstain from officially announcing his 
candidacy. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

