<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 2 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0302175194 </F>
<F P=103> PA0302175194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Salvadoran economic developments monitored through 2 
February; source follows in parentheses after each item. 
  The Salvadoran economy has been growing at a rate of 5 
percent for the last two years, which denotes a strong economic 
growth in all areas, according to Central Reserve Bank (BCR) 
spokesmen. Economic growth was reported mainly in the areas of 
construction, services, the manufacturing industry, and 
commerce. "The country is no longer dependent on foreign aid. 
The U.S. reduction in aid should not have a major impact on the 
economy," the BCR spokesmen have said. (San Salvador EL DIARIO 
DE HOY in Spanish 27 Jan 94 p 29) 
  The cost of living increased by 1,115 colons in the past 
four 
years, showing that the economic growth mentioned by the 
government has not helped the poor. According to investigations 
conducted by the Consumer Protection Center (CDC), the poor in 
El Salvador do not benefit from the country's economic growth. 
Purchasing power has dropped by 18 percent in rural areas due 
to the inflation rate in the past few years. There has been a 
16-percent drop in urban areas, and there is a concentration of 
wealth in a few hands, the CDC states. (San Salvador Radio 
Venceremos Network in Spanish 1800 GMT 27 Jan 94) 
  Salvadoran exports reached $1.022 billion in 1993, which is 
$448 million more than in 1989, the BCR announced on 31 January. 
Guatemala is the leading importer of Salvadoran products, 
according to the BCR. Forty-two percent of all exports in 1993 
went to Central America, 30 percent to the United States, and 7 
percent to Germany. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2324 GMT 31 Jan 
94) 
  Official sources said on 2 February the Salvadoran 
Government 
increased credits for the agriculture sector by $199,000 in the 
last four years. The BCR said the sector received $149,000 in 
credits in 1989, but in 1993 it had increased to $348,000. A 
BCR communique also stated there was an increase in the 
production of basic grains from 18.4 million quintals in 1989 to 
more than 21 million quintals in 1993. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in 
Spanish 2059 GMT 2 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32285 </DOCNO>
