<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon Reacts to U.S. Human Rights Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402042594 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
0400 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402042594 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Ramiro De Leon Carpio and other 
high-ranking government officials reacted to the U.S. State 
Department's report on Guatemala this Wednesday. The president 
responded to a reporter's question about the report and the 
activities of the Civilian Self-Defense Patrols. 
  [Begin De Leon recording] The State Department report says 
many things [words indistinct]. You have referred to one of 
them; that is, possible human rights violations by the Army, 
Civilian Self-Defense Patrols, and security forces personnel in 
general. The report only mentions the issue but does not include 
any specific information or evidence. The State Department has 
done the same with Peru and other countries. We are reviewing 
[words indistinct] and I am studying it. The report includes 
several recommendations that are acceptable and, admittedly, 
several of the things mentioned are realistic. However, 
responsibility for human rights violations falls on the state 
itself -- be it this state or any other -- thus the report says 
nothing new. 
  Regarding the Civilian Self-Defense Patrols, the government 
is willing -- especially this year, when we expect to sign a 
peace agreement -- to eliminate them gradually. They have 
already started to be turned into [word indistinct] legal peace 
and development committees. However, the most important issue 
is that [words indistinct] patrol members who commit crimes, 
just as any Guatemalan citizen, will be tried and punished if 
found guilty. 
  The State Department and the international community already 
know this. We sent a letter sent to President Clinton 
specifically expressing our willingness to improve the situation 
and outlining the positive steps taken by the government. This 
is alluded to in the report. As I recall, it mentions somewhere 
that there is hope and that with the arrival of President Ramiro 
De Leon Carpio, there has been a reversal in the attitude of the 
Guatemalan Government. Thus, the report is not entirely 
negative. We believe in some cases [words indistinct] is 
correct but in others, it is a bit speculative. The report does 
not present sufficient arguments or evidence to back its 
assertions. 
  Just like any other State Department report, we will have to 
study and review it. We will look at its ramifications and the 
annotations and suggestions it makes to several ministries 
regarding labor, economic, and social issues, on special [words 
indistinct], assembly plants, and so forth. I would say it is 
more or less a repetition of the reports that the State 
Department has issued every year for the past three or four 
years. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32286 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat024_h_94001" </HT>


