<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calm Returns After Nationwide Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402151694 Paris AFP in Spanish 1347 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0402151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 4 Feb (AFP) -- Ecuador began this Friday with 
complete calm following a nationwide workers strike yesterday to 
reject a recent 71.2-percent increase in gasoline prices. This 
morning sanitation workers were removing debris left from the 
barricades erected by demonstrators in the streets. 
  Activities were returning to normal as urban buses began 
providing service. On Thursday the buses paralyzed a large part 
of the country when they stopped operating to avoid being 
damaged by demonstrators. 
  There were no major incidents as rightist Ecuadoran 
President 
Sixto Duran-Ballen confronted the third workers strike in the 
first 18 months of his administration, which will conclude in 
August 1996. On Saturday Duran-Ballen implemented a price 
increase from 1,460 to 2,500 sucres (from $0.71 to $1.22) a 
gallon (3.785 liters) for the most widely used gasoline in the 
country. This measure was rejected by political, social, 
student, and labor sectors. More than 12 demonstrators and 20 
policemen were injured during the clashes, which also caused 
heavy damage to public and bank buildings in Quito and the port 
of Guayaquil. 
  The United Workers Front (FUT), which includes the most 
powerful labor federations, ordered the 24-hour strike to demand 
wage increases and the cancellation of the fuel price hike. It 
announced it is planning another nationwide strike in the next 
few days for an indefinite period, as well as an empty-pot march 
by housewives and an Indian uprising [levantamiento de 
indigenas], scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday respectively. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32296 </DOCNO>
