<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Police Promotions Splits Senate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0402162994 La Paz Radio Fides Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0402162994 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Radio Fides Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jaime Murillo] </F>
  [Excerpts] During a closed-doors session, the Senate 
yesterday approved the promotion of two police chiefs to the 
rank of general. MIR [Movement of the Revolutionary Left] and 
Condepa [Conscience of the Fatherland] senators walked out of 
the session that dragged on until nearly midnight because they 
challenged the promotion of two officers. Those promoted to the 
rank of general are Colonel Luis Rocha Martinez -- who is 
mentioned as the most likely candidate for the post of police 
commander -- and Colonel Rogelio Vargas -- whose candidacy was 
questioned by MIR and Condepa due to his involvement in the 
thwarted burning of precursors in the Huanchaca case. The 
Senate did not approve the promotion of Colonel Willy Arriaza -- 
whose candidacy was also questioned by the parties that walked 
out of the session. [passage omitted] 
  Condepa Senator Andres Solis Rada said: 
  [Begin recording] I want to report that Condepa and MIR 
senators walked out of the Senate session because senators of 
the MNR [Nationalist Revolutionary Movement] and UCS [Solidarity 
Civic Union] ruling coalition joined forces with ADN 
[Nationalist Democratic Action] to promote Col. Arriaza, who 
worked as Arce Gomez's [interior minister under General Luis 
Garcia Meza] aide at the time of the terrible Harrington Street 
massacre which claimed the lifes of eight young MIR members. 
[passage omitted]. 
  They even wanted to overrule the Bolivian Police command who 
believe only two officers should be promoted. Our decision to 
leave the session was instrumental in making the Senate stop and 
think about this. In the end only two officers were promoted. 
[passage omitted] [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

