<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Raul Castro, Politburo Members Visit Guantanamo Province </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0402165194 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1000 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0402165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Army General Raul Castro, second secretary of the 
Central Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba [PCC] and FAR 
[Revolutionary Armed Forces] minister, has inaugurated the 
nation's first center for mountain-area research and 
development. This center, built at a cost of over 13 million 
pesos, is located in the Limonar area of El Salvador 
Municipality, Guantanamo Province. 
  In a speech she made at the inauguration ceremony, Rosa 
Elena 
Simeon, member of the PCC Central Committee and president of the 
Cuban Academy of Sciences, emphasized that one of the center's 
objectives is to intensify the work aimed at increasing 
production of foodstuffs, both traditional and new, for human 
consumption. Simeon also announced that a scientific hub will be 
created soon in Guantanamo Province. 
  Raul also visited the organic plots located in Montesano. 
The 
plots are aimed at rendering the Caribe area, near the city of 
Guantanamo, self-sufficient in food. 
  Raul was accompanied by Politburo members Juan Almeida, vice 
president of the Council of State; General Ulises Rosales del 
Toro, first vice minister of the FAR and head of the general 
staff; Esteban Lazo and Julian Rizo, respectively PCC first 
secretaries in the provinces of Santiago de Cuba and Camaguey; 
Agriculture Minister Alfredo Jordan; Juan Carlos Robinson, 
member of the Central Committee and PCC first secretary in 
Guantanamo Province; and other leaders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

