<H3> <TI>   Lage on Meeting With Franco, U.S. Embargo on Vietnam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0502025794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0502025794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cuban Vice President Carlos Lage Davila described 
the conversations held with Brazilian President Itamar Franco 
and three ministers of his cabinet as very positive. On the 
third day of his official visit to Brazil, Lage held a press 
conference with more than 20 local and foreign reporters at the 
residence of the Cuban ambassador to Brazil. Of his meeting with 
Itamar Franco, Lage said they discussed many issues related to 
the development of political and economic relations between the 
two states. Furthermore, he stated that, even though no 
agreements would be signed during this visit to Brazil, doors 
have been opened for the development of bilateral ties. 
  Tomorrow morning, Lage Davila and the delegation that 
accompanies him will travel to Rio de Janeiro, where they will 
hold meetings with local businessmen and political personalities. 
  When questioned on the lifting of the U.S. embargo on 
Vietnam, the Cuban leader answered that it is the result of the 
Asian country's perseverance in keeping alive their ideals and 
social system. 

</TEXT>

