<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies President Comments on Visit by U.S. Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0402234194 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0402234194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] To kill two birds with one 
stone, the U.S. ambassador went to the lower chamber to meet 
with the new president of the Chamber of Deputies. However, they 
did not reach the common position that was the case at the upper 
chamber, because William L. Swing and Frantz Robert Monde 
expressed differing points of view on the Haitian crisis and the 
measures adopted by the international community. President 
Monde, once more, called on the Americans for more humaneness 
toward Haiti and solicited the lifting of the embargo: 
  [Begin recording] [Monde] It is the richest country in the 
world, the most prosperous, the most powerful that is imposing 
economic sanctions on the weakest, poorest one on earth. We 
asked him to ask the international community to view the crisis 
on a more humane angle -- the unfairness, the human aspect of 
the embargo -- the solution to the crisis in order to avoid a 
social explosion, according to critics of the policy of the 
international community which is adhering to the Governors 
Island accord. 
  [Reporter] What was the ambassador's answer? 
  [Monde] The same: It is not our fault; it is the military's 
fault. However, they did not realize that their approach to the 
crisis was greatly biased, which explains the fact that they 
have personalized the crisis as between two men, making a 
solution very difficult. [end recording] 
  This visit by the U.S. ambassador comes at a time when the 
Chamber of Deputies has basically resumed normal operations, 
while the Senate of the Republic is heading for a new rupture 
that is becoming more and more imminent. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

