<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Allows Journalists, Red Cross To Enter Town </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0502195394 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1530 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0502195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Freddy Martin Perez] </F>
  [Text] Guadalupe Tepeyac, Mexico, 5 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- The 
self-styled Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] allowed 17 
journalists into this area in observance of the agreement with 
Manuel Camacho Solis, commissioner for peace and reconciliation 
in Chiapas State. 
  The caravan of journalists was received by some 150 
inhabitants in downtown Guadalupe de Tepeyac, a village in 
Chiapas State in southeastern Mexico. Local resident Manuel 
Jimenez Santis said that residents are hopeful that hostilities 
will end. The EZLN accepted Camacho Solis' proposal to create 
two "free zones" or neutral areas in San Miguel and Guadalupe 
Tepeyac and on 2 February ordered its followers to withdraw from 
both areas. 
  The peace commissioner's proposal stipulates that once the 
two "free zones" are created, the International Red Cross will 
begin humanitarian aid and support operations for the civilian 
population in these two places. Jimenez Santis said that 
several dozen Lacandona jungle inhabitants have transferred 
their sick for medical attention in response to the announced 
arrival within the next few hours of International Red Cross 
members. 
  Jimenez Santis summoned Manuel Camacho Solis, commissioner 
for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas State, to come and learn 
the communities' most urgent needs. "We peasants have no land, 
no work, we have no good food, housing, education, or health 
care. What we want now is peace," Jimenez Sanits said. 
  NOTIMEX toured several communities and was able to verify 
that food and medicines had become scarce, while here in 
Guadalupe Tepeyac, where about 160 [as published] inhabitants 
live, the Solidarity Hospital was unharmed by the conflict. 
  The Mexican Government and the EZLN have maintained a 
cease-fire since 12 January following armed clashes that began 
on 1 January and left, according to official reports, about 100 
persons dead. Maria Gomez Hernandez, a housewife, said milk, 
sugar, rice, flour, oil, and other basic staples are urgently 
needed. She requested that Camacho Solis visit the area to work 
within the peace process in communities isolated by the conflict. 
  Possibilities increased this weekend for the first direct 
talks between the EZLN and the peace commissioner. "The 
dialogue may start," Camacho Solis said when announcing last 
night that both sides agreed on the discussion agenda after the 
EZLN proposed on Friday to include the topic of "national 
political life" without seeking agreements on this point. 
  In a message broadcast from San Cristobal de las Casas, 
1,200 
km southeast of Mexico City, Camacho Solis said that the 
contents for the direct dialogue "is the agenda on which we have 
mutually agreed." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32337 </DOCNO>
