<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Denies Authorizing Diplomat To Leave </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402144694 San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 3 Feb 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402144694 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Salvadoran Foreign Ministry in no way 
authorized the departure of Major Ismael Lopez. It was only 
after he had left that the U.S. Embassy informed the Ministry 
that Lopez had departed but without specifying how, Salvadoran 
Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Salaverria told LA PRENSA GRAFICA. 
In addition, Salaverria said the U.S. Embassy has been asked to 
explain how Lopez left the country. 
  Salaverria pointed out that the Foreign Ministry has no 
jurisdiction over who leaves the country and that this is the 
Immigration Department's duty. He said that, according to 
international law, Maj. Lopez, who allegedly killed bodyguard 
Crescencio Diaz, enjoys diplomatic immunity and that therefore 
he will be tried in the United States. "Maj. Lopez' diplomatic 
immunity precludes his being interrogated in El Salvador," 
Salaverria said. He also said that the Foreign Ministry had 
checked Lopez' diplomatic immunity in the Ministry's files. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

