<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Protests U.S. Official's Departure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402193594 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish 1800 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402193594 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "YSU Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Salvadoran Foreign Ministry released a 
communique at noon [1800 GMT] today confirming that the U.S. 
Embassy kept the Ministry abreast of the incident in which Major 
Ismael Lopez's bodyguard was killed. The document asserts that 
authorization was never requested for the U.S. officer to leave 
the country because the U.S. Embassy only kept the foreign 
minister abreast of the situation by telephone. 
  Upon confirming the incident, the U.S. Embassy promised the 
Salvadoran Foreign Ministry to prosecute the officer in 
accordance with U.S. legislation as stipulated under the Vienna 
Convention. Despite the official explanations provided by the 
U.S. Embassy, the communique states, the Salvadoran Government 
is not fully satisfied. Consequently, a letter of protest has 
been sent to the Clinton administration demanding penalties 
against the individuals who violated El Salvador's laws, 
especially its immigration laws. 

</TEXT>

