<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Denies Rumors of Military Coup </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0502165094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1615 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0502165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 5 Feb (Notimex) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio denied rumors related to a 
possible coup by military officers dissatisfied with current 
Defense Minister Mario Enriquez. 
  According to de Leon, the democratic process in Guatemala is 
going through a period of great consolidation and stipulated 
that he has not been requested to remove the defense minister, 
whom he considers to be one of his most trusted allies. 
  Local radio stations, citing confidential sources, reported 
that a group of military officers "dissatisfied with Enriquez' 
management style had called for his dismissal or there would be 
a coup during the next few days." 
  The radio reports contrast sharply with the calm in the 
streets adjacent from the presidential palace and the government 
house where security measures remain normal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

