<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD Announces Alliance With Liberal Republican, Labor Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402171594 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 31 
Jan 94 p A-1 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Carmen Elida Contreras] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday, the opposition party Democratic 
Revolutionary Party [PRD] announced they will form an alliance 
with the Liberal Republican Party and the Labor Party [Pala]. 
According to PRD presidential candidate Ernesto Perez 
Balladares, this alliance will be the great coalition against 
hunger, unemployment, and mismanagement. 
  Balladares stated: "I believe the great alliance will be one 
against hunger, unemployment, neglect, and government 
inefficiency, and the alliance is already formed." 
  At a meeting of the National Directorate, some 296 PRD 
members approved their party's alliance with Pala and the 
Liberal Party and confirmed their support for the presidential 
ticket headed by Perez Balladares with Tomas Gabriel Altamirano 
Duque and Felipe Virzi as first and second vice presidents, 
respectively. 
  Perez Balladares criticized Arnulfist Party candidate Mireya 
de Gruber's and former comptroller general Ruben Dario Carles' 
programs. Carles is supported by the Civic Renewal Party, 
Molirena [Nationalist Liberal Republican Movement], and the 
National Renewal Movement [Morena]. Balladares argued the two 
tickets reflect "the official state of affairs and contain the 
same proposals but in different packages." 
  Perez Balladares, who did not reject the possibility of 
other 
nonofficial groups joining his alliance before 8 February, said: 
"It is not a matter of sharing the cake, but of sharing an idea, 
a program. It is a matter of reaching an agreement as to the 
basis for a program." 
  Perez Balladares criticized candidates such as Carles, de 
Gruber, and Arias Calderon, who "live in and cling to the past" 
and who "will blatantly fail in 1994" when the problems and 
situations have changed. 
  The PRD's directorate reiterated its support for mayoral, 
legislator, and alternate-legislator candidates nominated by its 
new allies. 
  Meanwhile, Pala, which also held its political convention 
yesterday, restated its decision to form an alliance with the 
PRD and the Liberal Republican Party, and nominated the Perez 
Balladares-Altamirano-Virzi presidential ticket. 
  Pala President Carlos Lopez Guevara pointed out that 
although 
Pala is not represented on the presidential ticket, all the 
members support a "Torrijist alliance" to reach power together 
next May. 
  At its convention yesterday, the Republican Liberal Party 
unanimously supported the alliance and presidential ticket led 
by Perez Balladares. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32378 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat025_j_94004" </HT>


