<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects U.S. Report on Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402141694 Managua Radio Nicaragua Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0402141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Nicaragua Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "This Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Ernesto Leal Sanchez has 
announced the Nicaraguan Government rejects the U.S. State 
Department's report on human rights and other topics of national 
life regarding our reality. The Nicaraguan foreign minister said 
a note will be sent very soon to the U.S. Government rejecting 
the report. 
  [Begin recording] [Leal] We believe the report is not fair. 
We find the report unacceptable. It reports things that occurred 
in the past, but it tends to imply there is a systematic policy 
of human rights violations in our country. We find reports by 
Amnesty International and other organizations are more objective 
in their analysis. 
  [Unidentified Reporter] Does the Nicaraguan Government 
reject 
the part of the report which says that military authorities are 
not under civilian control? 
  [Leal] Well, basically, we cannot accept that either. You 
have heard and read the president's speech from 2 December 1993. 
What we are trying to do here is institutionalize and 
professionalize the Armed Forces. In fact, very soon the 
executive branch will be sending the Legislative Assembly a 
draft law on the military organization process and social 
security for the military. 
  [Reporter] Does this mean relations with the United States 
are not good? Why has the White House drafted a report which 
says human rights are being violated in Nicaragua? 
  [Leal] I do not think relations with the United States will 
sour because of the report. We do not agree with the report. We 
are not saying violations have stopped. Unfortunately, there are 
still cases of human rights violations in our country. The 
government is completely convinced and determined, however, to 
ensure strict respect for human rights. 
  [Reporter] Will the government take steps to reject the 
report? 
  [Leal] We are drafting a response to the document, 
certainly. 
What [U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American 
Affairs] Mr. Watson has said in the past few months is 
completely different from what the State Department is saying 
now. This document, which you should have, relates the cases 
that occurred in 1993. It refers, for instance, to 
confrontations between recontras and recompas. It refers to 
clashes between Sandinists and non-Sandinists, which we all know 
have occurred in the rural areas of our country. This does not 
mean, however, that the government wants these things to happen. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

