<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Carles Proposes Commissions To Investigate Corruption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0402182694 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 3 Feb 94 p 1a </F>
<F P=103> PA0402182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hermes Sucre Serrano] </F>
  [Text] Molirena [Nationalist Liberal Republican Movement] 
presidential candidate Ruben Dario Carles has advocated the 
creation of special commissions to investigate the scandal with 
the Social Security Fund's (CSS) housing projects, the National 
Financial Corporation's (COFINA) operations, and the Van Dam 
Bridge project. 
  According to the former comptroller general, the 
recommendations that the Directorate for the Recovery of State 
Property (DRP) made to the Legislative Assembly must be made 
again. These recommendations found no fertile ground before and 
were rejected. In a document entitled, "The Position of 
Presidential Candidate Ruben Dario Carles With Regard to 
Corruption," the Molirena politician explains his views about 
the creation of commissions to speed up the cases on dealings 
investigated by the Comptroller's Office and the DRP. 
  Carles also recommended adopting legislation concerning 
seized funds. These funds should be deposited at the National 
Bank and used to finance social projects. With regard to legal 
matters, Carles proposed profound changes to the penal and 
judicial codes. As to the Fiscal Code, he maintained that it 
must be modified in the area that pertains to contracts in which 
the public sector is a party. 
  He also proposed serious regulation of the civil service 
system to improve bureaucracy. According to Carles, corruption 
does not only mean stealing but providing bad service. 
  Concerning the administration of justice, Carles noted that 
since the outset of the democratic government in December 1989 
the Attorney General's Office has experienced a continuous 
crisis, one that "reached a climax with the investigation, 
trial, and ruling on the case of former Attorney General Rogelio 
Cruz. However, this did not end the crisis at the Attorney 
General's Office. This government office is safeguarding dozens 
of millions of dollars linked to drug trafficking or money 
laundering without making any progress in the investigations 
that are to lead to the respective trials," he stressed. 

</TEXT>

