<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria Says U.S. Troops' Presence No Violation of 
Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0602041294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1737 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0602041294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 5 Feb (EFE) -- Colombian 
President Cesar Gaviria has said the presence of the U.S. 
soldiers in Colombian territory does not violate the country's 
Constitution, because there is no transit of troops and their 
mission is to provide technical assistance and do engineering 
work. 
  Gaviria, in a letter sent to the State Council, which has 
asked him for explanations, has said the presence of U.S. 
military personnel on the Pacific Coast and in the eastern 
plains is in accordance with international treaties that have 
been formally accepted by Colombia in the past. 
  In a long document, Gaviria rehashes the legal evolution of 
the international law and the Colombian legislation, saying the 
operations of mutual defense and military assistance do not 
require authorization from the Senate or State Council. 
  Gaviria refers to the work by the U.S. soldiers at the beach 
town of Juanchaco (Valle Del Cauca Department), where they are 
building a school, a medical center, and a road, and in Puerto 
Lopez (Meta Department), where they are building a river port. 
  "The U.S. soldiers are not in the country to execute warlike 
activities against third parties," but their presence is in 
accordance with agreements for technical cooperation to supply 
logistic support so that the Colombian authorities may fight 
crime, he adds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32394 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat025_o_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-025 </AU>
