<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guatemalan Rebel Commanders Meet With Onusal Chief </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802043894 San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network in 
Spanish 1800 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0802043894 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Farabundo Marti Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Facing the Moment" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A high-level Guatemalan guerrilla commission met 
with Augusto Ramirez Ocampo, the UN Observers for El Salvador 
[Onusal] mission chief this morning. The Guatemalan National 
Revolutionary Unity [URNG] delegation was headed by Commanders 
Gaspar Ilom and Pablo Monsanto and members of the rebel 
diplomatic commission. 
  Augusto Ramirez Ocampo reported that the URNG delegation had 
come to learn of the role played by the United Nations in the 
verification of the Salvadoran peace process. On his part, 
Commander Rodrigo Asturas, alias Gaspar Ilom, said the agreement 
signed by the URNG and the Guatemalan Government on 10 January, 
allowed them to anticipate a positive future for the 
negotiations. 
  [Begin Asturias recording] [Words indistinct] specially 
significant to us, especially based on our evaluation of the 
Salvadoran negotiations and peace process. At the same time, we 
wanted to verify, in situ, the United Nations' weight in this 
peace process. In our case, we asked for UN participation as 
soon as we initiated talks in Guatemala. We ratified our 
request in the agreement signed on 10 January. We have called 
on the United Nations to act as a mediator in the process and 
this, of course, includes verification of all the agreements. 
[end recording] 
  URNG Commander Gaspar Ilom, who is the son of Miguel Angel 
Asturias, a nobel laureate for literature, considered that the 
UN experience in verifying the implementation of the agreements 
in El Salvador is promising. Ilom said the Guatemalan peace 
process will be very complicated but not, as a result of this, 
irresolvable. He added that they hope to reach agreements 
leading to peace very soon. Ilom insisted that the main points 
of the negotiation are to establish the role of the Army in a 
democratic society, the country's economic problems, and issues 
related to the Indian problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

