<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Calls for Guerrero Indians' Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0702125094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0349 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0702125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas (Mexico), 5 Feb (EFE) -- 
Today, the rebel Zapatist National Liberation Army (EZLN) called 
on Indian groups from the southern Mexican state of Guerrero to 
join their struggle. "Do not abandon us, do not let us die 
alone, do not let our struggle end in a vacuum," the EZLN said 
in a message released today, Saturday, and sent to the executive 
coordinating commission of the Guerrero State Council of Indian 
and Peasants Organization. 
  The communique came in reply to a letter by Guerrero Indian 
organizations, which includes representatives from the Amusgo, 
Mixtecos, Nahuatls, and Tlapenecos ethnic groups, and was 
delivered to the EZLN by its intermediary [Monsignor] Samuel 
Ruiz, bishop of San Cristobal de las Casas. 
  The EZLN called on the Guerrero Indian organizations to 
"take 
our blood as nourishment, fill your hearts and the hearts of all 
good men of this Indian and non-Indian land," but does not 
specify the type of support they request. "Brothers, let our 
path be the same for all: liberty, democracy, justice," the 
Zapatistas added. 
  Guerrero, located approximately 300 km south of Mexico City, 
is one of the states most analysts believe will show evidence of 
the EZLN movement. Recently, local police initiated an operation 
to search for guerrilla hideouts in this state's mountainous 
region. 
  The last Mexican guerrilla rebellion occurred in Guerrero in 
1970 with the Party of the Poor, founded by Lucio Cabanas, a 
rebellion subsequently controlled by the Armed Forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

