<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Communique Requests Peace Cordons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0702163794 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1530 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0702163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1530 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Text" of communique issued by the Indian Revolutionary </F>
Clandestine Committee-General Command of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN] to all nongovernment organizations and 
signed by Subcommander Marcos on 1 February; place not given -- 
read by announcer] 
  [Text] The Indian Revolutionary Clandestine 
Committee-General Command of the EZLN respectfully addresses you 
all to make a polite request. As everyone knows, the initiation 
of the peace dialogue between Mr. Manuel Camacho Solis and the 
EZLN is imminent. The fact that the dialogue is being held in a 
conflict area implies provocation risks that could hinder or bog 
the talks down. 
  With the purpose of minimizing unwanted rifts between the 
parties in conflict, it is necessary to form around the talk 
site a security or peace cordon, which can prevent the pressure 
or intimidation of one of the parties in conflict. We know the 
so-called nongovernment organizations have remained neutral in 
the present conflict, and they have always been concerned about 
the need to alleviate the serious conditions of the civilian 
population as well as to promote the peace efforts with dignity 
as sought by our forces and all honest Mexicans. 
  For the reasons mentioned above, we would like to 
respectfully ask you to form a peace cordon that can prevent 
both federal troops as well as those from the EZLN from meddling 
in the region surrounding the negotiation table. Let it be 
understood that this does not represent any commitment or 
support for our struggle's cause, and that we will continue to 
respect and greet your neutrality and humanitarian duty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

