<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Drug Money Alleged in Congressional Campaigns </TI></H3>
<H4>   * Cauca, Atlantic Coast Said Affected </H4>
<F P=102> 94P20340A Santa Fe de Bogota EL ESPECTADOR in Spanish 5 Jan 
94 p 5A </F>

<F P=103> 94P20340A </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL ESPECTADOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] The principal drug cartels are said to be financing 
the election campaigns of some candidates for the Congress, 
especially in Cauca Department. 
  The allegation about the influence of hot money [dinero 
caliente] in the political campaigns was made by Juan Jose Chaux 
Mosquera, currently a member of the House of Representatives. 
  The Liberal politician spoke with Fernando Garcia, this 
paper's correspondent in Popayan, and told him that in Cauca 
dirty money is already circulating in politics. 
  He lamented that several candidates for public office are 
accepting money from "friends of drug trafficking, which could 
impede peaceful debate, since it will lead to political 
corruption." 
  Although Chaux Mosquera did not reveal the list of persons 
aspiring to congressional office who are allegedly receiving 
financial backing from drug traffickers, he said it is easy to 
identify them since they are handing out large sums of money in 
northern Cauca. 
  In the halls of Congress there were insistent rumors during 
the last weeks of legislative activity that relatives of persons 
who have been linked to drug trafficking would be running for 
congressional office, especially in the Atlantic Coast region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

