<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Drug Money Alleged in Congressional Campaigns </TI></H3>
<H4>   * Allegations Continue </H4>
<F P=102> 94P20340B Santa Fe de Bogota EL ESPECTADOR in Spanish 6 Jan 
94 p 5A </F>

<F P=103> 94P20340B </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL ESPECTADOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Cauca representative Edgar Papamija Diago reaffirmed 
yesterday that it is certain that some political campaigns in 
northern Cauca Department are being financed with hot money. 
  He said that "the consciences of many persons from several 
municipalities have been bought off, having in mind the 1994 
election campaign." 
  The legislator supported the statements made by his 
colleague 
Juan Jose Chaux Mosquera who was one of the first to denounce 
the presence of drug money in political circles. 
  Papamija Diago promised to cooperate with Chaux Mosquera to 
investigate and reveal the names of those politicians who are 
buying votes, apparently with money obtained from drug 
trafficking. 
  Meanwhile, Senator Humberto Pelaez Gutierrez, a Liberal 
leader in northern Cauca, said that "one should bear in mind 
whether Congressman Chaux Mosquera made the statements while 
intoxicated or while sober," and Pelaez Gutierrez hopes to begin 
investigations aimed at clearing up such statements. 

</TEXT>

