<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Samper Rejection of U.S. Military Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0702004294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1555 GMT 6 Feb 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0702004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 6 Feb (PL) -- Two presidential 
hopefuls from the ruling Liberal Party reiterated today their 
rejection of the U.S. military presence in Colombia, where there 
are 259 U.S. soldiers stationed, according to official figures. 
  Ernesto Samper, former economic development minister under 
President Cesar Gaviria, and favored to win his party's 
nomination for the presidential candidacy, said a fast one was 
pulled on the president and he asked himself if the one who did 
it was the U.S. Government or the Defense Ministry. 
  He added that "fast one pulled on the president was 
unfortunately pulled on all Colombians, who feel we have been 
harmed by this undue interference by the United States." 
  As for the reiterated official explanation that the largest 
contingent of troops, made up of 156 men stationed in Juan Chaco 
on the Pacific coast, came to build a school and a health 
center, he said it is "simply outrageous and no Colombian is 
willing to believe that story." 
  Another Liberal Party presidential hopeful, Humberto de la 
Calle, much closer to Gaviria, said that "since before the Juan 
Chaco situation emerged, I asked for the suspension of the 
operation because just as I feared, it created an atmosphere of 
inadvisable suspense and suspicion." 
  He pointed out that work on social projects can perfectly 
well be in the hands of the Colombian Army and he added that 
Gaviria's explanations for the case have created an atmosphere 
of confusion. 
  "What I believe should be condemned are the half truths, the 
quasi clandestine way of handling it, and the absence of clear 
information for Colombians," he added. 

</TEXT>

