<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Castro Closes Meeting, Addresses Regional Debt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2901034894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2354 GMT 28 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2901034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 28 Jan (PL) -- Today in Havana, Cuban 
President Fidel Castro said creditors are collecting Latin 
America's foreign debt twice, and the continent has lost the 
better part of this great battle. 
  Closing the Fourth Latin American and Caribbean Meeting, 
which has been in session in Havana since Tuesday, the topmost 
leader of the revolution recalled it was said in a great forum 
held in Havana in 1985 that this debt could not be collected and 
could not be paid off. He said: Our continent has lost the 
better part of this great battle. We are being charged in ever 
increasing amounts. 
  He recalled that when the Cuban Revolution triumphed in 1959 
Latin America's debt was very small, and now it amounts to $500 
billion. He said our countries' basic products had a certain 
value in the world market at that time. The current great 
technologies have gradually displaced them. To illustrate, he 
said sugar has been substituted by substances like isoglucose 
[isoglucosa], extracted from corn and whose sweetening power is 
greater than that of beet and cane sugar. 
  Castro spoke at the plenum in the presence of more than 
1,000 
delegates from 32 countries. 

</TEXT>

