<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   UJC First Secretary Cites Students' Debates on Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2701185094 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1513 GMT 24 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2701185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Zenaida Ferrer Martinez] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 24 January (PL) -- Students of junior high 
schools, high schools, and universities have begun debating the 
country's urgent economic topics and have joined the Cuban 
parliament, which is meeting to discuss financial and economic 
topics. 
  In an interview granted to PRENSA LATINA, Juan Contino, 
first 
secretary of the Union of Young Communists (UJC), has announced 
that stemming from the grassroots organizations of the 
respective student federations, this segment of the population 
is also expressing its concerns and proposals regarding complex 
aspects of Cuba's economy. 
  He said a large part of the 500,000 members of the UJC 
belong 
to the worker and peasant sector. They are participating in 
this analysis in response to an appeal by the Cuban Workers 
Federation (CTC). 
  Contino said it is incredible to see the diversity of 
opinions that emerge in these forums and how youths between the 
ages of 14 and 25 (approximately pre-university and university 
level) state opinions on ways to reduce money in circulation 
based on experience in their own fields. Their views are then 
submitted to group analysis. 
  Contino said disagreements do occur but do not pose 
antagonizing views, because they stem from an identity of 
principles and actions of historic generations of the revolution 
and the younger generation. 
  With the integration of students into these debates, the 
national consensus is expanded to promote decisions that permit 
balancing the fiscal deficit of some $4.2 billion pesos 
(equivalent to dollars at the official rate of exchange) and 
cutting excessive money in circulation by 10 billion pesos. 
  The youth leader said although the Federation of Midlevel 
School Students (FEEM) and the University Students Federation 
(FEU) are autonomous and independent organizations, youths who 
belong to these organizations are more attracted by UJC 
activities. 
  He said adolescents and youths between the ages of 25 and 30 
require more attention. The former because they are at that age 
between childhood and adolescence, full of complications, and 
the latter because they are not interested in big parties or 
large gatherings, 
  This is reflected in recreation, he explained, where though 
discotheques in the country have increased to 37 and though 
there are 100 recreational facilities in the country, the 
particular demands of the different age groups of a population 
of 5.7 million residents from 0 to 30 years have yet to be met. 
  The 33-year-old economist, together with the person heading 
the UJC in lieu of current Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina, has 
the assessment of recreational facilities, given that the last 
congress was positive, despite the fact that resources were 
drained by the country's difficult economic situation. 
  He said, nonetheless, approximately 2 million people have 
enjoyed recreational activities sponsored by the youth 
organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

