<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802174394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0802174394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Salvadoran economic developments monitored through 8 
February 1994. 
  The Central Reserve Bank today reported that 42 percent of 
El 
Salvador's overall exports go to Central America, 30 percent to 
the United States, 7 percent to Germany, while the remainder are 
distributed among several other nations. The bank also reported 
that Guatemala is El Salvador's main trading partner. 
Meanwhile, exports to Mexico doubled over the past two years 
from $8 million to $16 million in 1993. The bank also reported 
that the GDP rose 5 percent in 1993, and it is expected to 
increase 6 percent in 1994. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2047 
GMT 1 Feb 94) 
  An economic analysis indicates that exports have doubled 
from 
1989 to 1993, going from $600 million to more than $1.1 billion. 
This translates into a better standard of living and more 
resources for the people and the nation. Overall export growth 
has been driven by an increase in nontraditional exports, 
particularly in the assembly plant sector. Also, while coffee 
prices have fallen, coffee exports have increased. (San 
Salvador Canal Doce Television in Spanish 0300 GMT 4 Feb 94) 
  Roberto Orellana, president of the Central Reserve Bank, 
reports the Multisector Investment Bank will open its doors 
within the next few days with capital amounting to 300 million 
cordobas. The bank's goals are to contribute to economic growth 
and to generate jobs by financing capital investments in the 
private sector. Orellana reports that the bank will receive a 
$30 million credit from the International Development Bank to 
implement a program to bolster small businesses. This new 
banking institution will only grant loans to the private sector 
for investment projects. (San Salvador LA PRENSA in Spanish 4 
Feb 94 p 3) 
  The agricultural sector has moved from a severe, decade-long 
recession in the 1980's to growth in the 1990's. Among those 
product groups that have shown signs of growth are basic grains, 
coffee, and sugar cane. An increase in the number of manzanas 
cultivated nationwide helped increase the overall harvest from 
18.4 million quintals in 1989 to more than 21 quintals in 1993. 
In addition, credits to the agricultural sector have increased 
from 1.3 million colones in 1989 to 3.2 million colones in 1993. 
(San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY in Spanish 4 Feb 94 p 13) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

