<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lage Scheduled To Meet With Venezuelan President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0802160294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1000 
GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0802160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cuban Vice President Carlos Lage will meet with 
Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera today in Caracas. Lage 
arrived in Venezuela from Brazil, where he met with President 
Itamar Franco and other government officials, political leaders, 
and local businessmen. 
  Venezuelan media have reported that Caldera has the 
intention 
of maintaining good relations with Cuba. In Caracas, Lage will 
also meet with Venezuelan Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Burelli, 
who aspires to become secretary general of the Organization of 
American States and who has recently declared that he favors the 
reintegration of Cuba into that Panamerican association. 
  Another important meeting that Lage will hold during his 
brief stay in Venezuela will be with the directorate of the 
Petroleos enterprise to examine the possibilities of resuming 
the triangular oil trade that existed between Caracas, Moscow, 
and Havana. In statements to the press in Rio de Janeiro, prior 
to his departure for Caracas, Lage pointed out that every day 
the United States is more isolated in its policy of blockade 
against Cuba. He added that an example of this is the passage of 
resolutions against Washington's economic retaliations against 
Havana by the UN General Assembly for two consecutive years. 
  Today, Lage will travel to Colombia on an official visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

