<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate President Reaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0802205794 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0802205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Senate Office has learned over the radio that a 
pirate Senate office has been formed. The alleged objective of 
this pirate office is to hamper the operations of the existing 
Senate institution. 
  According to a note signed by Senator Firmin Jean-Louis, 
steps already taken could at last lead to a denouement to the 
crisis ravaging Haiti. 
  The Senate Office invites the country's institutions and the 
entire Haitian people not to let themselves be led into any 
adventurist maneuvers, which can only plunge the country even 
further into the abyss and delay the process of setting up a new 
government, returning to constitutional and democratic order, 
lifting the embargo, and having the country move toward progress 
once and for all. 
  The Senate Office takes this opportunity to announce to the 
nation that a parliamentary delegation has gone abroad. The 
delegation will meet with representatives of the United Nations, 
the OAS, and the governments of the United States, Canada, 
France, and Venezuela to explore ways and means of getting out 
of the crisis quickly. 
  The communique adds: Furthermore, the Senate Office has 
decided, pending the decision of the assembled Senate, to 
suspend Senator Ebrane Cadet, Senate Office first secretary, who 
has destroyed his reputation vis-a-vis the population through 
his undisciplined and dangerous behavior toward the institution. 
  The Office of the Senate of the Republic firmly believes 
that 
the results of the multiple steps being taken abroad by the 
parliamentary delegation should calm apprehensions and fulfill 
everyone's expectations. 
  This note is signed: Firmin Jean-Louis, senator of the 
Republic, president. 

</TEXT>

