<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peru: Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802164994 </F>
<F P=103> PA0802164994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Peruvian economic developments monitored through 8 
February. 
  Today, the director of the National Statistics and 
Information Technology Institute said inflation for January was 
1.84 percent. This, he notes, indicates that inflation 
"continues to go down." The sectors that showed higher increases 
in January were rent, fuel, electricity, transportation, 
communication, and health care services while those that 
increased but not as much were food, beverages, entertainment, 
and cultural services. (Lima Global de Television Network in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 2 Feb 94) 
  On Thursday, the Peruvian Central Reserve Bank reported that 
as of 25 January, Peru's international reserves increased to 
$2.847 billion. This is $146 million more than the amount 
registered at the end of December. (Paris AFP in Spanish 1627 
GMT 3 Feb 94) 

</TEXT>

