<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duran-Ballen Says Economic Measures Will Remain Unchanged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802153994 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0802153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpt] President Sixto Duran-Ballen has reiterated that 
despite protests by government officials, the economic measures 
will not be changed. Duran-Ballen said he will not change his 
mind about the measures. He said that if the Court of 
Constitutional Guarantees determines the measures are 
unconstitutional, the government will appeal the decision to the 
Supreme Court of Justice, which will have the final word. The 
Court of Constitutional Guarantees will submit a final report on 
the demands presented by three political parties regarding the 
unconstitutionality of the economic measures adopted by the 
government. 
  When questioned about the protests, Duran-Ballen stated the 
government will not allow tantrums, and he said emergency 
measures will be taken if deemed necessary. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

