<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Economy Ministry Opens Deregulation Office </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20345B </F>
<F P=103> 94P20345B </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Managua BARRICADA in Spanish of 25 
January 1994 on page 4 reports that the Ministry of Economy and 
Development (Mede) has opened a deregulation office to reduce 
red tape based on input from businessmen to facilitate the 
distribution of goods. For example, representatives of the 
Cristal biscuit factory complained that the Ministry of 
Agriculture and Livestock required an export certificate which 
was not required by the country to which their products are 
exported, while fishing industry representatives are seeking to 
abolish permits required for exports to the United States, which 
does not require a similar document, according to the article. 
Mede Vice Minister Enrique Brenes explains that, in addition to 
eliminating trade barriers, the office is sponsoring training 
seminars for entrepreneurs. 

</TEXT>

