<H3> <TI>   Presidential Hopefuls' Reactions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802201494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0802201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statements by Colombian presidential hopefuls, who were </F>
asked if President Gaviria had made a mistake in allowing the 
presence of U.S. soldiers; from the "National" newscast; 
speakers identified by caption -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Ernesto Samper, Liberal Party] The situation is 
particularly outrageous in areas like Buenaventura where there 
is a 60 percent unemployment and underemployment rate. We do not 
need to bring in labor forces, not even to carry out exercises. 
  [Humberto de la Calle, Liberal Party] I think this sort of 
operation was mishandled from the very beginning. It should have 
been clearly explained and not with half-truths. 
  [Miguel Maza Marques, Conservative Party] Besides blowing it 
by allowing their presence, the country has been lied to. This 
is, in my opinion, a doubly unfortunate position by the 
president. 
  [Gabriel Melo, Conservative Party] That was a shameful 
agreement. Foreign troops were granted permission to bear arms, 
use all ports and airports, and conduct emergency night flights, 
according to the agreement. All this to build a small school? 
  [Carlos Lemos, Liberal Party] The country has not been told 
the truth. Proof of this is that when the defense minister 
returned to work after a heart ailment, he told the country that 
it was about time to clarify what had happened in Juanchaco and 
other parts of the nation. 
  [Enrique Parejo, Conservative Party] I do not think they 
fooled the president. Who knows what is behind all this. 
Therefore, it is important the president explain. 

</TEXT>

