<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802165094 </F>
<F P=103> PA0802165094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 8 
February. 
  Corabastos (expansion unknown; involves supplies) reports 
that in January the price of 30 basic staples increased by 
between 0.5 and 204 percent. On 1 February, the DANE (National 
Administrative Department of Statistics) released a report on 
the cost of living for January showing a considerable increase 
in food prices, which could raise the cost of living index by as 
much as 3.5 percent. Meanwhile, Cesar de Hart Vengoechea, 
president of the Association of Colombian Farmers, said the 
consumer index was low because of the sacrifices of the farming 
sector and low profits. He said the opposite would be true with 
increased prices and farmers would be able to make a little 
profit. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO in Spanish 1 Feb 94 p 
2B) 
  During January, food and transportation prices increased the 
most and the consumer index increased 3.15 percent. This 
increase was .09 percent lower than the same period in 1993 when 
a 3.24 increase was recorded, which raises the government's 
hopes of meeting its goal of 19 percent inflation in 1994. DANE 
Director Rodolfo Uribe says the index was affected primarily 
because the price of vehicles, gasoline, parking lots fees, 
tires, etc. increased 9.23 percent. Prices in the health sector 
increased the most in areas like consultation, hospitalization, 
lab tests, and dental services. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO 
SIGLO in Spanish 2 Feb 94 p 1, 1B) 

</TEXT>

