<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon Rejects Rumors of Division in Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0802224394 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1941 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0802224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 8 Feb (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro De Leon Carpio today rejected rumors of 
divisions in the Armed Forces and confirmed that the Army plays 
an important role in consolidating and strengthening democracy. 
De Leon thus countered newspaper reports of a split in the Army 
created by peace talks between the government and guerrillas. 
Rumor has it that the Army has split into three factions: the 
first being the military personnel who were removed following 
the self-inflicted coup attempt by the later deposed President 
Jorge Serrano in 1993, the second being the "hard-liners," and 
the third being those who support institutional rule. 
  According to SIGLO VEINTIUNO, the "hard-liners" oppose talks 
with the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Alliance [URNG] and 
support the president, but only on certain conditions. The 
newspaper says those military personnel are willing to join the 
removed officers to resume armed field actions against the 
guerrillas if the government gets the United Nations more 
involved in the peace talks. According to an agreement signed 
between the guerrillas and the government in Mexico on 10 
January, the United Nations will moderate the peace talks, which 
are scheduled to resume early in March. 
  The president labeled the reports as false and added: "I am 
not worried about rumors. I am convinced that the officers are 
aware of the role they play in the democratic process. There 
could be differences of opinion, but no division." De Leon said 
the Army feels fully responsible for the country's institutional 
order. 
  The president spoke at the Main Square in front of the 
government building shortly before meeting with Monsignor 
Prospero Penados del Barrio, Archbishop of Guatemala. De Leon 
said the Archbishop's visit was of a personal nature, although 
they would also discuss subjects related to the country's 
political, economic, and social crisis. 
  Defense Minister General Mario Rene Enriquez has also 
reiterated the Army's support for peace talks but opposed the 
creation of a truth commission to investigate human rights 
violations perpetrated since armed conflict began in 1960. 
  De Leon said discussions on human rights with URNG will have 
to include all related aspects, but he declined to give any 
additional details. 
  Finally, Gen. Enriquez said the Armed Forces object to the 
creation of a truth commission because it would disregard the 
Army and would polarize rather than assuage the population. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
